## Bibliography & Index (pp. 241–245)

> These final pages contain only the Bibliography (concluding entries) and the
> book's Index. No new arguments, models, or evidence appear here.

### Bibliography — Notable Works Referenced (selected)

- **Ibn Khaldun** — *The Muqaddimah* (1958 trans.) — foundational theorist of
  asabiyyah and dynastic cycles; cited throughout the book as a precursor to
  Turchin's own secular cycles framework
- **Goldstone, J. A.** — *Revolution and Rebellion in the Early Modern World*
  (1991) — key source on demographic-structural theory and state breakdown
- **Taagepera, Rein** — two 1978 papers on empire size/duration systematics
  and growth-decline curves (3000 BC–600 BC); empirical backbone for
  Turchin's territorial dynamics model
- **McNeill, W. H.** — *The Rise of the West* (1963) and *Europe's Steppe
  Frontier* (1964) — geopolitical context for metaethnic frontier argument
- **Collins, R.** — 1995 prediction of Soviet collapse (*American Journal of
  Sociology*) — cited as evidence that macrosociological models can generate
  falsifiable predictions
- **Gumilev, Lev** — *Ethnogenesis and Biosphere* (1971, Russian) — source for
  the ethnogenesis/asabiyyah parallel Turchin draws with his own model
- **Kennedy, Paul** — *The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers* (1987) —
  imperial overstretch framing
- **Fischer, D. H.** — *The Great Wave* (1996) — price revolution cycles;
  tested against Turchin's secular cycle model for medieval/early modern Europe
- **Tilly, Charles** — *Coercion, Capital, and European States* (1990) —
  state formation theory; frequently cited alongside Turchin's own frontier
  ethnogenesis mechanism
- **Putnam, R. D.** — *Making Democracy Work* (1993) and *Bowling Alone*
  (2000) — social capital and trust as collective-action foundations
- **Malthus, T. R.** — *Essay on the Principle of Population* (1798) —
  foundational demographic pressure logic underpinning the secular cycle
- **Le Roy Ladurie, Emmanuel** — *The Peasants of Languedoc* (1974) —
  empirical long-run French demographic data
- **Wrigley & Schofield** — *The Population History of England: 1541–1871*
  (1981) — primary data source for English secular cycle analysis
- **Goldstein, J.** — *Long Cycles* (1988) — Kondratieff-style wave dynamics
- **Boyd & Richerson** — multiple papers (1985–2002) on cultural evolution,
  group norms, reciprocity, and punishment — theoretical grounding for
  Turchin's asabiyyah as an evolved cultural trait
- **Tainter, J. A.** — *The Collapse of Complex Societies* (1988) — complexity
  and diminishing returns framing for imperial decline

